  "prompt": "How is it that the density of water is exactly 1kg/litre?",
  "response": "The density of water being exactly **1 kg/litre** is not a coincidence but rather a result of how the metric system was defined. Here's the explanation:\n\n1. **The Metric System and Definitions**:\n   - In the metric system, the **kilogram (kg)** was originally defined as the mass of 1 litre of water at its maximum density (which occurs at around **4\u00b0C** under standard atmospheric pressure).\n   - This means that by definition, **1 litre of water at 4\u00b0C** has a mass of **1 kilogram**.\n\n2. **Density Formula**:\n   - Density is defined as mass per unit volume:  \n     \\[\n     \\text{Density} = \\frac{\\text{Mass}}{\\text{Volume}}\n     \\]\n   - Since 1 litre of water has a mass of 1 kilogram, the density of water is:  \n     \\[\n     \\text{Density of water} = \\frac{1 \\, \\text{kg}}{1 \\, \\text{litre}} = 1 \\, \\text{kg/litre}\n     \\]\n\n3. **Historical Context**:\n   - The metric system was designed to be simple and practical. By linking the kilogram and the litre in this way, measurements of mass and volume became directly relatable for everyday use, especially for water.\n\n4. **Scientific Precision**:\n   - While the density of water is exactly 1 kg/litre by definition, in practice, the density of water can vary slightly with temperature and pressure. For example, at **20\u00b0C**, the density of water is approximately **0.998 kg/litre**, and at **100\u00b0C**, it\u2019s about **0.958 kg/litre**.\n\nIn summary, the density of water is exactly **1 kg/litre** because the metric system was intentionally designed to make this relationship true by definition. This makes it easier to convert between mass and volume for water in everyday measurements.",
